	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=139782><span id=Sage>vikeshta</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>16 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I would have to say that Charisma doesn't really play a role in the field for a necromancer.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the city and at merchants around the game, having a high CHA can save you many platinum over the lifespan of your character, so you may want to get items that help raise your CHA for those occasions. A pair of <a href=HTTP://everquest.allakhazam.com/db/item.html?item=12035 target=_new>Opal Encrusted Steins</a> will raise your CHA by a whoppping <b>50 points</b>.  At that rate, the merchant will be more influenced by your faction.<br><br>Charisma is believed to assist in charm spells, though as necro, this will affect your ability to charm undead, the only creatures you can charm -- they may break charm more easily, or the charm may not last as long.  However, I posit that such situations are rare, so don't worry about it.<br><br>Fear is not based on Charisma in any way.  After all, you're not scaring it from the force of your personality (or lack of it): you're using magic to screw with its brain.  At least, that's how I look at it.<br><br>Neanne de Sule<br>Citizen of the <a href=HTTP://www.foolsrepublic.com target=_new>Fools Republic</a><br>The Nameless</p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
