	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=97459><span id=Guru>Warric</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>313 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I have seen this question argued very passionately by others time and again, and there never seems to be an answer to satisfy everyone, but I trust certain sources, such as Morty at <a href=HTTP://www.necrognomicon.com/ target=_new><b>Necrognomicon - The Book of Dead Gnomes</b></a>.<br><br><BLOCKQUOTE><b id=fs8>Quote:</b><hr size=1><b>Charisma</b><br>Merchants are hopeless pushovers, offering better prices in response to high Charisma and a smile, while covering their losses by overcharging those people with low Charisma. Pathetic. A few enchanter spells and bard songs are influenced a bit by Charisma; however, testing has never demonstrated an effect on any necromantic spells, specifically regarding the Fear line and the Dominate Undead line.<br><br>Charisma is for high elf wimps who couldn't strike terror into the heart of a Rivervale child even if they ripped out their own brains and set them on fire.<hr size=1></BLOCKQUOTE><br>Heheh. Such a way with words, that Morty.<br><br>Well, you're still left with questions beyond the ones you posed here.&nbsp;&nbsp;Whose opinion is authorative?  Who are we to believe?<br><br>As I have personally seen no appreciable difference resulting from raising or lowering my Charisma (other than the difference in merchants' prices), I choose to accept the explanation put forth by Morty, and likeminded others, and get on with Death's business, concentrating my efforts on raising the attributes that form the core of my powers.<br><br>Whichever you choose, good luck to you.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Fri Jan 17 11:05:06 2003</em></p>&nbsp;<br>So long and thanks for all the fish.</td></td></tr>
