	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Thu, Dec 26th 11:36 AM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=92022><span id= >Lord Mesit</span></a><br><span id=notbold>11 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Hello all Mighty Necros,<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;Here is a bit of help from a hunble necro on learning how to fight with your necro in a group.  Your necro can be used as a Druid/Monk in group pulling.  It is a good idea if you have never played a Druid or monk to find someone that can teach you, a guild member or a friend who has a high lvl that can teach you.  You can snare and and FD to break pulls.  <br>  Also I wanted to tell you that I think that Necro's are amazing group players.  One of the best in the game.  You can do much more than almost any other single player in the game, witch is why they solo so easy.  We can give mana to the healer, snare, MASS dot, mez, FD, and a whole lot more.  So if you are a soloing freak then give groups a try it is a whole lot more fun.  I am a lvl 35 Necro and have played all classes and my Necro is by far the funest, with the most options, to play.  If anyone knows a great place at 35 for groups please let me know.<br><br>Vazelle<br>35 Necro Morthantos<br>Lords of Dragons</p>&nbsp;<br>The hills will flow with the blood of the nonbeleiver.<br>53(Baron) Necro Morthantos(Vazelle)<br>51 War <br>Morlof(Vazelle)</td></td></tr>
	     <tr><td colspan=2 align=right class=mform id=fs8>1 Replies</td></tr>
	     </form></table><tr><td colspan=2><ul><table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td>
	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=/cgi-bin/mrate.pl name=f104443507019421>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes.html?class=14&mid=104443507019421>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=14&mid=104443507019421>RE: necro's and grouping</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=14&mid=104443507019421#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Wed, Feb 5th 4:21 AM 2003</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=139782><span id=Sage>vikeshta</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>16 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I, too, would like to say that necromancers can bring a great deal to a group.&nbsp;&nbsp;Despite our reputation as soloers, it is our versatility that can benefit a group that's missing some key skills.<br><br><b>Pulling</b>: Yes, necros can pull.  We have FD and we have a snare.  Done correctly, a necro can pull something back to the group without getting damaged.  Unless you're fighting undead, or a rare mob that doesn't wander away, snare it!  This is typically a druid or ranger's job, but necro snare has the advantage of doing damage at the same time.<br><br><b>Healing</b>: 'Necros aren't healers!' No, they're not primary, or even secondary, healers in most groups.  But, in odd group configurations or in clutch situations, you <b>can</b> help keep a group member alive.  Necromancers have two lines of health spells: Straight health injections and a reverse lifetap over time.  Both work by draining the necromancer of his/her health and giving it to the recipient.  Sure it hurts.  But that's why you turn right around the lifetap the mob that's beating on your tank.  There have been a few groups where my necro was the primary healer -- and we did just fine.<br><br><b>Crowd Control</b>: Necromancers receive a mez spell at level 24 (Screaming Terror) which, like enchanter and bard mez spells, puts a mob out of action for a while. It lasts 24 seconds and has a long recast time, so necros aren't the best to handle 4 adds.  But, when a little timing and little luck (i.e. no resists), a necro can keep a pair of adds docile until the group is ready.  Necromancers also receive root in their 30s, which can be used to park a mob that just doesn't want to wait for its beating.<br><br><b>Twitching</b>:  Nobody likes being called a twitch bitch, but the fact remains, necros are one of two(?) classes that can transfer mana to another caster.  This is handy when your mob is spell resistant: you can dump your mana on the healer to keep your tanks alive.  Or perhaps the mob is almost dead, but so is your tank -- a little bit of mana to the healer or perhaps to the nuker to put that beastie down could mean the difference between a hard-won victory or a total party corpse run.<br><br><b>Rez</b>: Yes, it's true!  A necro can rez!  Granted, you need a gem that comes from a 50+ character who sacrifices a level, but you never know.  I once saw a level 57 character announcing his departure from the game, so he was selling his gear and donating the cash to his guild.  He also opened up the floor to any high-level necros that wanted to Sacrifice him to get the necro rez gem.  <br><br>So, the point of this posting is to prove that necros aren't <b>just</b> about soloing.  The reason we solo well, is because we have a lot of skills.  These skills can benefit a group, and grouping can be fun.  EverQuest is a Multiplayer game for a reason -- you play with other players!  I believe that the mark of a good player isn't necessarily how fast you can level, but how well you can play your class in non-standard and high-pressure situations.  <br><br>Neanne de Sule<br>Citizen of the <a href=HTTP://www.foolsrepublic.com target=_new>Fools Republic</a><br>The Nameless<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Wed Feb  5 04:10:27 2003</em></p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
